{"subject_name":"Soil Science Temp","subject_id":25,"chapters":[{"chapter_name":"Chapter1","topics":[{"topic_name":"Importance of Soil Science","topic_html":"<section class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 content-section rounded-2 border\"><pre class=\"copy-container\" data-title=\"javascript\"><code class=\"language-javascript copy-text\">import { reverseContent } from '../allModule/reverse_content.js';\n\n/**\n * Saves the content of a topic within a chapter of the current subject.\n * Updates the topic HTML and triggers an update to the subject data.\n */\nexport async function save_content_handler() {\n    \n    trigger('#contentSaveBtn', async () =&gt; {\n        this.showStatus('Saving...', false);\n        const chapter = this.current_subject.chapters.find(ch =&gt; ch.chapter_name === this.current_chapter);\n        const topic = chapter ? chapter.topics.find(tp =&gt; tp.topic_name === this.current_topic) : null;\n        if (topic) {\n            topic.topic_html = reverseContent();\n            await this.updateSubject();\n        }\n    });\n}\n</code></pre></section>","topic_id":216,"last_visited":"2024-10-08T03:42:21.707Z"},{"topic_name":"MD","topic_html":"<section class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 content-section rounded-2 border\" data-markdown=\"true\" data-markdown-text=\"Certainly! Below is a comprehensive table of Markdown syntaxes, showcasing various features, their corresponding syntax, and examples of how they appear when rendered. This table will serve as a handy reference to help you utilize Markdown more effectively.\n\n---\n\n| **Feature**          | **Syntax**                                       | **Example**                             |\n|----------------------|--------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|\n| **Heading 1**        | `# Heading 1`                                    | # Heading 1                             |\n| **Heading 2**        | `## Heading 2`                                   | ## Heading 2                            |\n| **Heading 3**        | `### Heading 3`                                  | ### Heading 3                           |\n| **Bold**             | `**bold text**` or `__bold text__`               | **bold text**                           |\n| **Italic**           | `*italic text*` or `_italic text_`               | *italic text*                           |\n| **Bold &amp; Italic**    | `***bold and italic***` or `___bold and italic___` | ***bold and italic***                 |\n| **Strikethrough**    | `~~strikethrough~~`                               | ~~strikethrough~~                       |\n| **Blockquote**       | `> Blockquote`                                    | > Blockquote                            |\n| **Ordered List**     | `1. First item`<br>`2. Second item`               | 1. First item<br>2. Second item         |\n| **Unordered List**   | `- First item`<br>`* Second item`                 | - First item<br>* Second item           |\n| **Inline Code**      | `` `inline code` ``                                | `inline code`                           |\n| **Code Block**       | <pre>```<br>code block<br>```</pre>              | ```<br>code block<br>```                |\n| **Horizontal Rule**  | `---` or `***` or `___`                            | ---<br>***<br>___                       |\n| **Link**             | `[link text](https://example.com)`                | [link text](https://example.com)         |\n| **Image**            | `![alt text](https://example.com/image.jpg)`      | ![alt text](https://example.com/image.jpg) |\n| **Table**            | See **Table Example** below                        | See below                               |\n| **Task List**        | `- [ ] Task 1`<br>`- [x] Task 2`                  | - [ ] Task 1<br>- [x] Task 2             |\n| **Footnote**         | `Here is a footnote.[^1]`<br>`[^1]: Footnote text` | Here is a footnote.[^1]<br>[^1]: Footnote text |\n| **Emoji**            | `:smile:`                                         | :smile:                                 |\n| **LaTeX**            | `$math$` for inline<br>`$$math$$` for block        | $math$<br>$$math$$                        |\n| **Nested List**      | `1. Item 1`<br> &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;`- Subitem A`          | 1. Item 1<br>   - Subitem A               |\n| **Horizontal Alignment in Tables** | `:---:`, `:---`, `---:` in table separator | | Column 1 | Column 2 |<br>| :---: | ---: |<br>| Center | Right-aligned |\n\n---\n\n### **Table Example**\n\nHere's how you can create tables in Markdown:\n\n```markdown\n| Header 1 | Header 2 | Header 3 |\n|:--------:|---------:|:--------|\n| Centered | Right-aligned | Left-aligned |\n| Data 1   | Data 2   | Data 3   |\n| Data 4   | Data 5   | Data 6   |\n```\n\n**Rendered Table:**\n\n| Header 1 | Header 2      | Header 3    |\n|:--------:|-------------:|:-----------|\n| Centered | Right-aligned | Left-aligned |\n| Data 1   | Data 2       | Data 3      |\n| Data 4   | Data 5       | Data 6      |\n\n---\n\n### **Detailed Breakdown of Features**\n\n1. **Headings**\n   - Use `#` symbols followed by a space to create headings. The number of `#` symbols denotes the level.\n     ```markdown\n     # Heading 1\n     ## Heading 2\n     ### Heading 3\n     ```\n\n2. **Emphasis**\n   - **Bold:** Wrap text with `**` or `__`.\n     ```markdown\n     **bold text**\n     __bold text__\n     ```\n   - **Italic:** Wrap text with `*` or `_`.\n     ```markdown\n     *italic text*\n     _italic text_\n     ```\n   - **Bold &amp; Italic:** Combine both.\n     ```markdown\n     ***bold and italic***\n     ___bold and italic___\n     ```\n\n3. **Strikethrough**\n   - Use `~~` to strikethrough text.\n     ```markdown\n     ~~strikethrough~~\n     ```\n\n4. **Blockquotes**\n   - Start a line with `>` to create a blockquote.\n     ```markdown\n     > This is a blockquote.\n     ```\n\n5. **Lists**\n   - **Ordered Lists:** Use numbers followed by periods.\n     ```markdown\n     1. First item\n     2. Second item\n     ```\n   - **Unordered Lists:** Use `-`, `*`, or `+`.\n     ```markdown\n     - First item\n     * Second item\n     + Third item\n     ```\n\n6. **Code**\n   - **Inline Code:** Wrap text with backticks `` ` ``.\n     ```markdown\n     `inline code`\n     ```\n   - **Code Blocks:** Use triple backticks or indent with four spaces.\n     ```markdown\n     ```\n     code block\n     ```\n     ```\n\n7. **Horizontal Rules**\n   - Create horizontal lines using `---`, `***`, or `___`.\n     ```markdown\n     ---\n     ***\n     ___\n     ```\n\n8. **Links and Images**\n   - **Links:** `[link text](URL)`\n     ```markdown\n     [OpenAI](https://www.openai.com)\n     ```\n   - **Images:** `![alt text](URL)`\n     ```markdown\n     ![Logo](https://example.com/logo.png)\n     ```\n\n9. **Tables**\n   - Define tables using pipes `|` and hyphens `-`.\n     ```markdown\n     | Header 1 | Header 2 |\n     |----------|----------|\n     | Cell 1   | Cell 2   |\n     | Cell 3   | Cell 4   |\n     ```\n\n10. **Task Lists**\n    - Use `- [ ]` for incomplete tasks and `- [x]` for completed tasks.\n      ```markdown\n      - [ ] Task 1\n      - [x] Task 2\n      ```\n\n11. **Footnotes**\n    - Reference footnotes using `[^1]` and define them elsewhere.\n      ```markdown\n      Here is a footnote.[^1]\n      \n      [^1]: This is the footnote text.\n      ```\n\n12. **Emojis**\n    - Use colons `:` to include emojis.\n      ```markdown\n      :smile:\n      ```\n\n13. **LaTeX**\n    - Include mathematical expressions using `$` for inline and `$$` for block.\n      ```markdown\n      Inline math: $E = mc^2$\n      \n      Block math:\n      $$\n      E = mc^2\n      $$\n      ```\n\n14. **Nested Lists**\n    - Indent sub-items with spaces or tabs.\n      ```markdown\n      1. Main Item\n         - Subitem A\n         - Subitem B\n      2. Another Item\n      ```\n\n15. **Inline HTML**\n    - Embed HTML directly within Markdown for more control.\n      ```markdown\n      <div style=&quot;color: red;&quot;>This is a red text.</div>\n      ```\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Tips**\n\n- **Escaping Characters:** Use a backslash `\\` to escape Markdown characters.\n  ```markdown\n  \\*This text is not italicized.\\*\n  ```\n\n- **Combining Features:** Markdown allows combining multiple features for complex formatting.\n  ```markdown\n  > **Bold Blockquote** with *italic* text and a [link](https://example.com).\n  ```\n\n- **Using HTML for Advanced Features:** While Markdown is versatile, certain advanced formatting might require HTML.\n  ```markdown\n  <table>\n    <tr>\n      <th>HTML Header</th>\n      <th>Another Header</th>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>HTML Cell</td>\n      <td>Another Cell</td>\n    </tr>\n  </table>\n  ```\n\n---\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nMarkdown is a powerful and flexible markup language that allows you to create well-formatted documents with ease. By mastering these syntaxes, you can enhance your documentation, blog posts, README files, and more. Practice combining different features to create rich and organized content effectively.\n\nFeel free to reach out if you have any questions or need further assistance with Markdown!\"></section>","topic_id":217,"last_visited":"2024-10-08T04:07:20.142Z"},{"topic_name":"MdMath","topic_html":"<section class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 content-section rounded-2 border\"><h3 class=\"\">Testing Math In Markdown<br></h3></section><section class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 content-section rounded-2 border\" data-markdown=\"true\" data-markdown-text=\"### Understanding Matrix Rank\n\n**Matrix rank** is a fundamental concept in linear algebra that measures the &quot;non-degenerateness&quot; of a matrix. More formally, the rank of a matrix is the maximum number of linearly independent rows or columns in the matrix. It provides valuable information about the solutions to linear systems, the invertibility of matrices, and the dimensionality of the vector spaces spanned by the matrix's rows or columns.\n\n**Key Points:**\n- **Row Rank and Column Rank:** Interestingly, the number of linearly independent rows (row rank) is always equal to the number of linearly independent columns (column rank) for any matrix. This common value is simply called the rank of the matrix.\n- **Full Rank:** A matrix has full rank if its rank is equal to the smallest of the number of its rows or columns. For example, an \\( m \\times n \\) matrix has full rank if its rank is \\( \\min(m, n) \\).\n- **Rank Deficiency:** If the rank is less than the maximum possible, the matrix is said to be rank-deficient.\n\nLet's delve into two examples to illustrate how to determine the rank of a matrix.\n\n---\n\n### Example 1: Determining the Rank of a 2x3 Matrix\n\n**Matrix \\( A \\):**\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\\\\n4 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\n**Step 1: Write the Matrix**\n\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\\\\n4 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\n**Step 2: Row Reduce to Echelon Form**\n\nWe aim to simplify the matrix using elementary row operations to identify the number of pivot positions (leading 1s).\n\n1. **Make the first element of the first row a pivot (already 1).**\n   \n2. **Eliminate the first element of the second row:**\n   - Multiply the first row by 4 and subtract it from the second row:\n     \\[\n     R2 = R2 - 4R1 = \\begin{bmatrix} 4 &amp; 5 &amp; 6 \\end{bmatrix} - 4 \\times \\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\end{bmatrix} = \\begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; -3 &amp; -6 \\end{bmatrix}\n     \\]\n   \n   The matrix becomes:\n   \\[\n   \\begin{bmatrix}\n   1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\\\\n   0 &amp; -3 &amp; -6 \\\\\n   \\end{bmatrix}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Normalize the second row pivot:**\n   - Divide the second row by -3:\n     \\[\n     R2 = \\frac{1}{-3} R2 = \\begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\end{bmatrix}\n     \\]\n   \n   The matrix is now:\n   \\[\n   \\begin{bmatrix}\n   1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\\\\n   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\\\\n   \\end{bmatrix}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Eliminate the second element of the first row:**\n   - Subtract 2 times the second row from the first row:\n     \\[\n     R1 = R1 - 2R2 = \\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\end{bmatrix} - 2 \\times \\begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\end{bmatrix} = \\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\end{bmatrix}\n     \\]\n   \n   Final echelon form:\n   \\[\n   \\begin{bmatrix}\n   1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\\\\n   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\\\\n   \\end{bmatrix}\n   \\]\n\n**Step 3: Count the Pivot Positions**\n\nThere are two pivot positions (one in each row). Hence, the **rank of matrix \\( A \\) is 2**.\n\n**Interpretation:**\n- The rows of \\( A \\) are linearly independent.\n- The column space of \\( A \\) is a 2-dimensional subspace in \\( \\mathbb{R}^2 \\).\n\n---\n\n### Example 2: Determining the Rank of a 3x3 Matrix\n\n**Matrix \\( B \\):**\n\\[\nB = \\begin{bmatrix}\n2 &amp; 4 &amp; 6 \\\\\n1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\\\\n0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\n**Step 1: Write the Matrix**\n\n\\[\nB = \\begin{bmatrix}\n2 &amp; 4 &amp; 6 \\\\\n1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\\\\n0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\n**Step 2: Row Reduce to Echelon Form**\n\n1. **Make the first element of the first row a pivot:**\n   - It's already 2. To simplify calculations, you can divide the first row by 2, but it's not necessary for determining rank. We'll proceed without scaling.\n\n2. **Eliminate the first element of the second row:**\n   - Multiply the first row by \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\) and subtract it from the second row:\n     \\[\n     R2 = R2 - \\frac{1}{2} R1 = \\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\end{bmatrix} - \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 4 &amp; 6 \\end{bmatrix} = \\begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\end{bmatrix}\n     \\]\n   \n   The matrix becomes:\n   \\[\n   \\begin{bmatrix}\n   2 &amp; 4 &amp; 6 \\\\\n   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\\\\n   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\\\\n   \\end{bmatrix}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Eliminate the second element of the first row:**\n   - Subtract 4 times the second row from the first row:\n     \\[\n     R1 = R1 - 4R2 = \\begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 4 &amp; 6 \\end{bmatrix} - 4 \\times \\begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\end{bmatrix} = \\begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 0 &amp; -2 \\end{bmatrix}\n     \\]\n   \n   Final echelon form:\n   \\[\n   \\begin{bmatrix}\n   2 &amp; 0 &amp; -2 \\\\\n   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\\\\n   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\\\\n   \\end{bmatrix}\n   \\]\n\n**Step 3: Count the Pivot Positions**\n\nThere are two pivot positions (one in the first row and one in the second row). The third row is entirely zeros and does not contribute to the rank. Hence, the **rank of matrix \\( B \\) is 2**.\n\n**Interpretation:**\n- Only two rows are linearly independent.\n- The column space of \\( B \\) is a 2-dimensional subspace in \\( \\mathbb{R}^3 \\).\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Matrix \\( A \\)** (2x3 matrix) has a rank of **2**.\n- **Matrix \\( B \\)** (3x3 matrix) also has a rank of **2**.\n\nIn both examples, the rank indicates the number of linearly independent rows or columns. Determining the rank involves row reducing the matrix to its echelon form and counting the pivot positions. Understanding the rank helps in solving systems of linear equations, determining matrix invertibility, and analyzing the properties of linear transformations.\" data-formula=\"true\"></section>","topic_id":218,"last_visited":"2024-10-08T04:32:43.021Z"}],"chapter_id":96}],"author":{"login":"Nh-emon","id":146737722,"node_id":"U_kgDOCL8KOg","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/146737722?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/Nh-emon","html_url":"https://github.com/Nh-emon","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Nh-emon/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Nh-emon/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Nh-emon/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Nh